[[File:Matsubara Shrine (Kasugai).JPG|thumb|right|150px|Torii of Matsubara Shrine]]
'''Matsubara Shrine''' (まつばらじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Kasugai|Q26101|qid=Q26101|1=Kasugai, Aichi}}, {{ill|lt=Aichi Prefecture|Q80434|qid=Q80434|1=Aichi Prefecture}}. It is identified with "Matsubara Tenjin" of Kasuharu District in the '{{ill|lt=Owari Kokunai Jinmyōchō|Q11041830|qid=Q11041830|1=Owari Kokunai Jinmyōchō}}', but another theory treats it as a {{ill|lt=candidate shrine|Q135022904|qid=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}} for "Takamu Shrine" in Kasugabe District of {{ill|lt=Owari Province|Q514506|qid=Q514506|1=Owari Province}} in the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'.

===History===
Tradition says it was founded on {{ill|lt=February 11 (lunar calendar)|Q839324|qid=Q839324|lt=lunar February 11|1=February 11 (Lunisolar)}} of {{ill|lt=Wadō|Q1373026|qid=Q1373026|1=Wadō (era)}} 4 ({{ill|lt=711|Q23519|qid=Q23519|1=AD 711}}), in the reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Genmei|Q233224|qid=Q233224|1=Empress Genmei}}. Because this area was then called "Takamu," it has been thought possibly to be the "'''Takamu Shrine'''" in the Engishiki register<ref>There is still a shrine called "Takamu Shrine" in {{ill|lt=Moriyama-ku|Q1155291|qid=Q1155291|1=Moriyama-ku, Nagoya}} of {{ill|lt=Nagoya|Q11751|qid=Q11751|1=Nagoya}}, but it is unknown which one is the shrine listed in the Jinmyōchō.</ref>.
In the medieval period, {{ill|lt=Inari worship|Q719665|qid=Q719665|lt=Inari faith|1=Inari Ōkami}} spread. As a result an Inari shrine was merged here as well, and it drew devotion under names such as "'''Takamu Inari Daimyōjin.'''
In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}, this area belonged to {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Inuyama Prefecture|1=UNKNOWN}}. In October Meiji 4 ({{ill|lt=1871|Q7746|qid=Q7746|1=1871}}), Inuyama Prefecture recognized it as the "Matsubara Shrine" in the '{{ill|lt=Kokunai Jinmyōchō|Q11420490|qid=Q11420490|lt=Owari Kokunai Jinmyōchō|1=Izumi Province Divine Name Register}}'. Inuyama Prefecture then merged with {{ill|lt=Nagoya Prefecture|Q11415214|qid=Q11415214|1=Nagoya Prefecture}} on {{ill|lt=November 22 (lunar calendar)|Q840493|qid=Q840493|lt=lunar November 22|1=November 22 (Lunisolar)}} of the same year. After {{ill|lt=Aichi Prefecture|Q80434|qid=Q80434|1=Aichi Prefecture}} was established, in October of the following Meiji 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|qid=Q7753|1=1872}}), this shrine became the gōsha of 18 nearby villages and was renamed "'''Matsubara Shrine.'''

